class Solution {
    public int lengthAfterTransformations(String s, int t, List<Integer> nums) {
        int res = s.length();
        for (int i = 0; i < t; i++) {
            StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
            for (char c : s.toCharArray()) {
                int index = c - 'a';
                for (int j = 0; j < nums.get(index); j++) {
                    sb.append((char) ('a' + (index + j) % 26));
                }
            }
            s = sb.toString();
            res = (res + s.length() - s.replaceAll(".{1}", "").length()) % 1000000007;
        }
        return res;
    }
}
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(t * s.length())
space complexity: O(s.length())
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution uses a brute-force approach to transform the string t times. In each iteration, it constructs a new string by replacing each character with the next nums[i] consecutive characters in the alphabet. The length of the resulting string is calculated by adding the length of the new string and subtracting the number of consecutive characters replaced. The result is taken modulo 10^9 + 7 to avoid overflow.

